                            <span style="color: #FFD700; font-weight: 700; font-size: 1.2rem;">Space and time are not separate! They're woven together as "spacetime" - and massive objects BEND spacetime like a bowling ball on a trampoline!</span>
                            <br><br>
                            <span style="font-size: 1.1rem;"><strong style="color: #FFD700;">Before Einstein:</strong> People thought gravity was a mysterious "force" that pulled objects together through empty space. Newton said "gravity pulls" but couldn't explain HOW or WHY.</span>
                            <br><br>
                            <span style="font-size: 1.1rem;"><strong style="color: #FFD700;">Einstein's Genius Idea:</strong> There is NO pulling force! Instead, massive objects bend the fabric of spacetime itself. Objects follow the curves in spacetime, like marbles rolling in a curved bowl. This explains WHAT gravity actually IS - it's geometry!</span>
                        </div>

                        <div class="explanation-box" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #4CAF50, #388E3C); color: white; border-left: 5px solid #FFD700;">
                            <strong style="color: #FFD700; font-size: 1.3rem;">üéØ Key Ideas of General Relativity:</strong><br><br>
                            <span style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 2;">
                            <strong style="color: #FFD700;">1. Spacetime is a Fabric:</strong> Space and time form a 4-dimensional fabric that can bend and curve.<br><br>
                            <strong style="color: #FFD700;">2. Mass Bends Spacetime:</strong> The Sun creates a "dip" in spacetime. Earth isn't being "pulled" - it's following the curved path in bent spacetime!<br><br>
                            <strong style="color: #FFD700;">3. Light Also Follows Curves:</strong> Even massless light bends when it passes near massive objects, because spacetime itself is curved!<br><br>
                            <strong style="color: #FFD700;">4. Time Runs Slower Near Massive Objects:</strong> Clocks tick slower on Earth than in space. Time itself is affected by mass!
                            </span>
                        </div>

